04066nam a22005295i 9780226248332DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20152015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262483327 a10.7208/97802262483322doi  a(DE-B1597)522726  a(OCoLC)907774356  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQL51.2.F8bG84 2016 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a590.7609443612231 aGuerrini, Anita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Courtiers' Anatomists :bAnimals and Humans in Louis XIV's Paris /cAnita Guerrini. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b35 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tA NOTE ON NAMES, DATES, AND OTHER MATTERS -- tABBREVIATIONS USED IN THE NOTES -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tIntroduction -- tONE. Anatomists and Courtiers -- tTWO. The Anatomical Origins of the Paris Academy of Sciences -- tTHREE. The Animal Projects of the Paris Academy of Sciences -- tFOUR. The Histoire des animaux -- tFIVE. Perrault, Duverney, and Animal Mechanism -- tSIX. The Courtiers' Anatomist: Duverney at the Jardin du roi -- tConclusion -- tEpilogue: The Afterlife of the Histoire des animaux -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Courtiers' Anatomists is about dead bodies and live animals in Louis XIV's Paris--and the surprising links between them. Examining the practice of seventeenth-century anatomy, Anita Guerrini reveals how anatomy and natural history were connected through animal dissection and vivisection. Driven by an insatiable curiosity, Parisian scientists, with the support of the king, dissected hundreds of animals from the royal menageries and the streets of Paris. Guerrini is the first to tell the story of Joseph-Guichard Duverney, who performed violent, riot-inducing dissections of both animal and human bodies before the king at Versailles and in front of hundreds of spectators at the King's Garden in Paris. At the Paris Academy of Sciences, meanwhile, Claude Perrault, with the help of Duverney's dissections, edited two folios in the 1670s filled with lavish illustrations by court artists of exotic royal animals. Through the stories of Duverney and Perrault, as well as those of Marin Cureau de la Chambre, Jean Pecquet, and Louis Gayant, The Courtiers' Anatomists explores the relationships between empiricism and theory, human and animal, as well as the origins of the natural history museum and the relationship between science and other cultural activities, including art, music, and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAnatomyxStudy and teachingzFrancezParisxHistory. 0aZoologyxStudy and teachingzFrancezParisxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226248332423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226248332.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles